def addSPNoise(im, percent):
    # Now, im is a PIL image (not a NumPy array)
    # percent is in range 0-100 (%)

    # convert image it to numpy 2D array and flatten it
    im_shape = im.shape  # keep shape for later use (*)
    im_vec = im.flatten()  # this is a 1D array # https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/differences-flatten-ravel-numpy/

    # generate random locations
    N = im_vec.shape[0]  # number of pixels
    m = int(math.floor(percent * N / 100.0)) # number of pixels corresponding to the given percentage
    locs = np.random.randint(0, N, m)  # generate m random positions in the 1D array (index 0 to N-1)

    # generate m random S/P values (salt and pepper in the same proportion)
    s_or_p = np.random.randint(0, 2, m)  # 2 random values (0=salt and 1=pepper)

    # set the S/P values in the random locations
    im_vec[locs] = 255 * s_or_p  # values after the multiplication will be either 0 or 255

    # turn the 1D array into the original 2D image
    im2 = im_vec.reshape(im_shape) # (*) here is where we use the shape that we saved earlier

    # convert Numpy array im2 back to a PIL Image and return it
    return im2
In[]:
def addGaussianNoise(im, sd=5):
    return im + np.random.normal(loc=0, scale=sd, size=im.shape)

def averageFilter(im, filterSize):
    mask = np.ones((filterSize, filterSize))
    mask = np.divide(mask, mask.shape[0]*mask.shape[1]) # can you think of any alternative for np.sum(mask)?
    # return ndimage.convolve(im, mask, 'float64')
    return ndimage.convolve(im, mask)

It is really interesting to see the differences in execution times. It seems that while the separate filter is constant with the filter size, the full filter is dependant of the filter size.

In[]:
def averageFilterSep(im, filterSize):
    maskh = np.ones((1,filterSize))
    maskv = np.ones((filterSize, 1))
    maskh = np.divide(maskh, maskh.shape[1])
    maskv = np.divide(maskv, maskv.shape[0])
    im2 = ndimage.convolve(im, maskv, 'float64') # For avoiding truncation errors.
    im3 = ndimage.convolve(im2, maskh, 'uint8') # Black & white images are arrays of uint8 data type in pillow.
    return im3

As you can see there is no appreciable difference in the image. But if you look at the difference between the two transformed images, with the sepparate and not separate filter there are suttle differences in some pixels that I think are related to the specifics of how the images are processed and transformed by numpy and scipy. Maybe some things related to some variations in data type transformations. Some operations are done using float64 type in numpy, but as images are defined as arrays with uint8 data there might be some differences as how some truncation or rounding errors might be treated. I had a lot of trouble with this exercise because at the begining I compared the resulting arrays instead of comparing the image plots. I spent hours trying to identify the problem because I though that if the arrays were not the same I made some mistake, until I realized the problem might be because of the data types and that the differences in the array were not appreciable when plotting the image.

def gaussianFilter(im, sigma=5):
    # im is PIL image
    # return ndimage.gaussian_filter(im, sigma, output='float64').astype('uint8') # If the output is float64 and then transformed to uint8 there are no rounding errors with respect to other methods
    return ndimage.gaussian_filter(im, sigma).astype("uint8")
In[]:
def gaussianFilterKernel(im, sigma=5):
    gv1d = signal.windows.gaussian(2 * round(4.0 * sigma) + 1, sigma).reshape(2 * round(4.0 * sigma) + 1, 1)
    gv2d = gv1d * gv1d.T
    gv2d = np.divide(gv2d, np.sum(gv2d))
    # return ndimage.convolve(im, gv2d, 'float64').astype('uint8') # this line is the same as the one below.
    return ndimage.convolve(im, gv2d).astype('uint8')
In[]:
def gaussianFilterKernelSep(im, sigma=5):
    gv1d = signal.windows.gaussian(2 * round(4.0 * sigma) + 1, sigma).reshape(2 * round(4.0 * sigma) + 1, 1)
    maskv = np.divide(gv1d, np.sum(gv1d))
    maskh = np.divide(gv1d.T, np.sum(gv1d.T))
    im2 = ndimage.convolve(im, maskh, "float64")
    # return ndimage.convolve(im2, maskv, "float64").astype('uint8')  # this line is the same as the one below.
    return ndimage.convolve(im2, maskv, "uint8")

Exercise 4

As you see the same is done for each filter. The data types returned are uint8. As you can also see there is no difference between the different versions. The first one is using a convolution like before a 2d mask over a 3 channel image. Broadcasting and vectorization solve all the problems of applying the filter to each channel. The second filter does a convolution for each channel. The fact that both filters give the same result makes it not really neccesary at all to writte another version of the filter for 3 channel color images.

In[]:
def gaussianFilterKernelSepColor(im, sigma=5):
    gv1d = signal.windows.gaussian(2 * round(4.0 * sigma) + 1, sigma).reshape(2 * round(4.0 * sigma) + 1, 1, 1)
    maskv = np.divide(gv1d, np.sum(gv1d))
    maskh = maskv.reshape(1, 2 * round(4.0 * sigma) + 1, 1)
    im2 = ndimage.convolve(im, maskv, "float64")
    return ndimage.convolve(im2, maskh, "uint8")
In[]:
def gaussianFilterKernelSepColor2(im, sigma=5):
    gv1d = signal.windows.gaussian(2 * round(4.0 * sigma) + 1, sigma).reshape(2 * round(4.0 * sigma) + 1, 1)
    maskv = np.divide(gv1d, np.sum(gv1d))
    maskh = maskv.T
    im2 = im.copy()
    for i in range(3):
        im2[:, :, i] = ndimage.convolve(im2[:, :, i], maskv, "float64")
        im2[:, :, i] = ndimage.convolve(im2[:, :, i], maskh, "float64")
    return im2.astype('uint8')

def showInGrid(imgs, figure_size=None, m=None, n=None, title="", subtitles=None):
    N = len(imgs)
    # plt.subplots_adjust(top=5) # aadido (10/10/19) para ejecutar una entrega de un estudiante
    m, n = computeRowsCols(N, m, n)
    # print(m,n)
    if figure_size is None:
        figure_size = (m, n)
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=figure_size)
    plt.gray()
    for i in range(1, N + 1):
        ax = fig.add_subplot(m, n, i)
        if len(imgs[i - 1].shape) >= 2:
            plt.imshow(imgs[i - 1])
        else:
            plt.plot(imgs[i - 1])
        if subtitles is not None:
            ax.set_title(subtitles[i - 1])

    fig.suptitle(title)
    # plt.savefig(title+".png")#,bbox_inches='tight')
    plt.show(block=True)

Exercise 7

It is easy to pass an argument with the two opossing vertex of the area we want to zoom in. Then the only thing left to do is to select the corresponding index of the image arrays.

There are many ways it can be improved, like cheking if the show argument is passed in a correct way or passing multiple vertex tuples one for each img in the imgs argument.

In[]:
def showInGrid(imgs, figure_size=None, m=None, n=None, show=None, title="", subtitles=None):
    N = len(imgs)
    # plt.subplots_adjust(top=5) # aadido (10/10/19) para ejecutar una entrega de un estudiante
    m, n = computeRowsCols(N, m, n)
    # print(m,n)
    if figure_size is None:
        figure_size = (m, n)
    # show is an argument that sets the two opossing vertex of the rectangle we want to zoom.
    if show is not None:
        for i in range(len(imgs)):
            imgs[i] = imgs[i][
                min(show[0][1], show[1][1]) : max(show[0][1], show[1][1]),
                min(show[0][0], show[1][0]) : max(show[0][0], show[1][0]),
            ]
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=figure_size)
    plt.gray()
    for i in range(1, N + 1):
        ax = fig.add_subplot(m, n, i)
        if len(imgs[i - 1].shape) >= 2:
            plt.imshow(imgs[i - 1])
        else:
            plt.plot(imgs[i - 1])
        if subtitles is not None:
            ax.set_title(subtitles[i - 1])

    fig.suptitle(title)
    # plt.savefig(title+".png")#,bbox_inches='tight')
    plt.show(block=True)
